Files:
- plugins/booking/src/booking-api.ts (update GraphQL error handler, lines 113-120)

Context:
Current error handler (lines 113-120):
  if (data.errors?.length && !data.data) {
    const msg = data.errors.map(e => e.message).join('; ');
    if (msg.includes('UNAUTHENTICATED') || msg.includes('401')) {
      clearAuthCache('booking');
      throw ToolError.auth(`GraphQL auth error: ${msg}`);
    }
    throw ToolError.internal(`GraphQL error: ${msg}`);
  }

When the CSRF token is stale, Booking.com returns a GraphQL error with a 403 CSRF_INVALID message. The current handler throws ToolError.internal (since it doesn't match UNAUTHENTICATED/401). This leaves the stale CSRF in the auth cache, causing ALL future mutations to also fail.

Fix:
  if (msg.includes('UNAUTHENTICATED') || msg.includes('401') || msg.includes('403') || msg.includes('CSRF') || msg.includes('FORBIDDEN')) {
    clearAuthCache('booking');
    throw ToolError.auth(`GraphQL auth error: ${msg}`);
  }

Or more broadly — check the HTTP status of the response and clear auth cache on any 403. Read the full graphql() function to understand how HTTP status and GraphQL errors are handled together.

Constraints:
- Do NOT change how the CSRF token is initially extracted from the SSR store (getAuth() reads it)
- The auth cache cleared here will be repopulated on the next getAuth() call, which re-reads the SSR store for a fresh token
- Do NOT change the ToolError.auth() throw — this is the right category (auth failure)
